830. Anaxagorae: b. at Clazomenae, about 500 ne. Anax· agoras taught that there is an indefinite number oi primitive sub· mances, qualitatively different, corresponding to all the various kinds oi matter. Thus, flesh is made up oi minute particles oi flesh, bone oi particles oi bone, gold ol gold, and so forth. These particles are underived and indestructible. They are not, however, atoms, ior they are infinitely divisible. The lour elements he thought to be merely a mixture of all kinds ol primitive particles; their “apparent simple· ness he explains by saying that, on account oi the amalgamation ot all possible determinate substances, not one of these is perceived in its distinctive individuality, but only that is perceived in which they all agree.” To explain the union oi these in living bodies, and the

creation and on-going ol the universe, Anaxagoras taught the exist· enee oi a Νοῦς, an incorporeal, intelligent Force, acting upon matter

lrorn without. He was the first who grasped at the idea oi essential difference between matter and spirit; at the conception also oi an intelligent Final Cause. It is an error, however, to suppose that Anaxagoras believed in the Νοῦς as a personality, as an infinite, all· perfect God. See Zeller, ‘Prae-Soc.
